+
+## 6. Field-state and profile-completeness model
+
+Blank is not a sufficient state.
+
+Every tracked field can be:
+
+- **known**;
+- **verified**;
+- **unverified**;
+- **unknown**;
+- **not applicable**;
+- **declined to disclose**;
+- **stale**;
+- **conflicting**;
+- **inherited or derived**;
+- **needs clarification**.
+
+Each value can carry:
+
+- source;
+- author or connector;
+- captured date;
+- verified date;
+- review due date;
+- confidence;
+- visibility;
+- purpose limitation;
+- change history.
+
+### 6.1 Context-specific readiness
+
+Liaison must not pressure users to fill every possible field.
+
+Readiness is calculated for a purpose:
+
+- basic contact readiness;
+- upcoming birthday readiness;
+- event catering readiness;
+- meeting briefing readiness;
+- travel briefing readiness;
+- family emergency readiness;
+- CardDAV export readiness;
+- workplace directory readiness.
+
+Example:
+
+```text
+Meeting briefing: 92% ready
+Missing: current priorities
+Stale: organization role last verified 18 months ago
+Not required: dietary profile
+```
+
+A person can be complete for one purpose and intentionally sparse for another.
+
+### 6.2 Missing-information queues
+
+Saved review views include:
+
+- high-priority people with no meaningful interaction;
+- people with no relationship type;
+- profiles with no organization or group;
+- family members with no important dates;
+- event attendees with unknown food coverage;
+- travel briefs missing required preferences;
+- records with stale employer or title;
+- profiles containing only a name;
+- fields with unresolved conflicts;
+- custom fields required by a selected profile template;
+- important contacts whose topic packs have never been reviewed.
+
+Bulk review must preserve `unknown`, `not applicable`, and `declined`; it must never translate them to empty or “none.”
+
+---
+
+## 7. Relationship intent, strength, and health
+
+### 7.1 Relationship intent
+
+Relationship Intent is explicitly authored by the user.
+
+Fields can include:
+
+- relationship type;
+- relationship tier;
+- manual importance from 0–5 or named tiers;
+- desired cadence;
+- desired future state;
+- preferred channel;
+- maintenance state;
+- boundaries;
+- do-not-contact or paused state;
+- next review date;
+- reason this relationship matters.
+
+Default tiers may be:
+
+- core;
+- active;
+- warm;
+- loose;
+- paused;
+- archive.
+
+Users can replace this vocabulary.
+
+### 7.2 Optional relationship assessment dimensions
+
+A user may manually assess dimensions such as:
+
+- closeness;
+- trust;
+- familiarity;
+- reciprocity;
+- shared context;
+- reliability;
+- current relevance;
+- emotional energy required;
+- desire for more or less contact.
+
+These dimensions are:
+
+- optional;
+- private by default;
+- timestamped snapshots rather than permanent truth;
+- never automatically disclosed;
+- never inferred solely from email volume;
+- shown in a semantic table if a visual chart is used.
+
+### 7.3 Maintenance status
+
+Maintenance Status is derived and explainable.
+
+Example states:
+
+- on track;
+- due soon;
+- overdue relative to chosen cadence;
+- open commitment;
+- upcoming important date;
+- stale context;
+- no cadence configured;
+- intentionally paused;
+- do not contact;
+- archived.
+
+The product should say:
+
+> “Quarterly cadence; last meaningful interaction was 112 days ago; one open commitment.”
+
+It should not say:
+
+> “Relationship strength: 42.”
+
+---
+
+## 8. Configurable Review Priority
+
+A numeric score may be used to order a review queue, but it must be named **Review Priority**, not Relationship Value or Human Value.
+
+### 8.1 Modes
+
+Users choose one of three modes:
+
+1. **Reason-only** — no number; cards are grouped by explainable reason.
+2. **Tiered** — low, normal, high, and urgent queue priority.
+3. **Weighted** — a configurable 0–100 ordering value with a complete component breakdown.
+
+Reason-only should be the default for personal use.
+
+### 8.2 Default weighted policy
+
+```text
+Review Priority =
+  30% cadence status
++ 20% manual importance
++ 20% open commitments
++ 10% upcoming important dates
++ 10% stale required context
++ 10% manual boost
+```
+
+Each component is normalized to 0–100 before weighting.
+
+Suppressions override the score:
+
+- archived;
+- do not contact;
+- paused until a date;
+- snoozed;
+- excluded from this review policy;
+- relationship ended.
+
+### 8.3 Component examples
+
+#### Cadence status
+
+```text
+0   = comfortably within cadence
+50  = cadence due today
+100 = overdue by one complete cadence interval or more
+```
+
+A user can select a different curve. Long-distance and low-frequency relationships should not be penalized when their desired cadence is yearly or none.
+
+#### Manual importance
+
+Named tiers map transparently:
+
+```yaml
+core: 100
+active: 75
+warm: 50
+loose: 25
+archive: 0
+```
+
+The mapping is editable.
+
+#### Open commitments
+
+Commitments can have urgency and due dates. A promise due tomorrow can surface a person even if contact occurred yesterday.
+
+#### Upcoming dates
+
+Birthdays, anniversaries, events, travel, and user-defined dates can raise review priority within a configurable window.
+
+#### Stale required context
+
+Only fields required by the active review purpose count. A missing airline preference must not raise the general friendship review queue.
+
+### 8.4 Explainability
+
+Every prioritized item shows:
+
+```text
+Why Alex is here
+- Quarterly contact cadence is 18 days overdue        +24
+- Core relationship tier                              +20
+- You promised to send the venue details              +16
+- Birthday is in 11 days                                +7
+- Job title has not been verified for 14 months         +4
+Total review priority: 71
+```
+
+The user can:
+
+- inspect the formula;
+- edit weights;
+- disable a component;
+- preview how a rule affects the queue;
+- create different policies for family, professional contacts, clients, an executive, or a workplace;
+- export and import the policy;
+- see policy version in historical review records.
+
+### 8.5 Guardrails
+
+The engine must not:
+
+- claim objective relationship strength;
+- infer affection, trust, or reciprocity from volume;
+- rank people for employment decisions;
+- produce employee performance or social-credit scores;
+- shame the user for overdue contact;
+- automatically send a message;
+- expose private scoring to a subject or shared workspace without explicit permission.
+
+---
+
+## 9. Review workflows
+
+### 9.1 Daily low-friction review
+
+The default daily view should contain a small capacity-bounded queue.
+
+User settings:
+
+- maximum people shown;
+- available social capacity: low, normal, high;
+- time budget;
+- work, personal, or mixed context;
+- hide overdue totals;
+- no-guilt language mode;
+- snooze entire review stream;
+- exclude weekends or quiet periods.
+
+Example card:
+
+```text
+Alex Murphy
+Reason: open commitment and birthday in 11 days
+Last meaningful topic: moving to a new role
+Suggested actions: open profile · log interaction · snooze · mark complete
+```
+
+No outreach text is sent without the user choosing it.
+
+### 9.2 Monthly relationship review
+
+The monthly review covers:
+
+- who was contacted;
+- who has become important;
+- who is no longer relevant to the current review policy;
+- which cadences are unrealistic;
+- which profiles are sparse or stale;
+- unclosed commitments;
+- upcoming dates;
+- possible introductions or resources to share;
+- people to archive, pause, or reconnect with;
+- policy weights that caused too much noise.
+
+The review is stored as a Markdown record with the policy version and selected decisions.
+
+### 9.3 Profile review
+
+The profile review screen groups fields by Topic Pack and state:
+
+- known and current;
+- missing for current purpose;
+- stale;
+- conflicting;
+- declined;
+- not applicable.
+
+It must support:
+
+- “mark not applicable”;
+- “ask later”;
+- “review after next interaction”;
+- “request from person,” where sharing is enabled;
+- bulk selection by group;
+- change history and source;
+- keyboard-only completion.
+
+### 9.4 Relationship review after an interaction
+
+The 30-second flow:
+
+1. log interaction;
+2. capture one-sentence summary;
+3. capture next step or no next step;
+4. optionally update last meaningful topic;
+5. optionally update one surfaced stale or missing field;
+6. calculate next due date from cadence or set manually;
+7. finish.
+
+The app must not turn every conversation into a data-entry session.
+
