+## 10. Filtering, grouping, and organization
+
+### 10.1 Universal filters
+
+Users can combine:
+
+- entity type;
+- person, organization, group, or household;
+- relationship type or tier;
+- maintenance status;
+- review priority range;
+- last interaction date/type;
+- next contact due;
+- important-date window;
+- organization, department, role, cost center, or location;
+- static or dynamic group;
+- topic-pack activation;
+- field state, including missing or stale;
+- tag;
+- event attendance;
+- connected resource type;
+- source or connector;
+- archived, paused, or do-not-contact state.
+
+### 10.2 Saved views
+
+Examples:
+
+- close friends not contacted within their own cadence;
+- high-priority professional contacts with no current organization;
+- people met at a conference who have no follow-up note;
+- family birthdays in the next 60 days with no gift ideas;
+- people with a dog but no dog name recorded;
+- executive contacts with an open commitment;
+- people with no meaningful interaction record;
+- organizations with no active member;
+- contacts whose profiles contain only imported phone data;
+- all people connected to a selected company or group within two graph hops.
+
+### 10.3 Graph behavior
+
+The graph includes:
+
+- people;
+- organizations;
+- groups;
+- households;
+- events and activities when enabled;
+- typed and directional relationships;
+- membership edges;
+- introductions;
+- shared events.
+
+The same data and actions must be available in an accessible table/tree. The graph is not the only operational interface.
